[[File:GH Walker logo.png|thumb|right|300px|G.H. Walker & Co. logo c.1922]]

'''G.H. Walker & Co.''' was an [[investment banking]] and [[brokerage]] firm founded in 1900 by [[George Herbert Walker]], grandfather and great-grandfather of [[President of the United States|Presidents]] [[George H. W. Bush|George Herbert Walker Bush]] and [[George W. Bush|George Walker Bush]], and located at [[1 Wall Street]].  

The firm was originally based in [[St. Louis, Missouri]].

In July 1973, the firm acquired the securities brokerage business of Laird, Inc.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1973/07/18/archives/g-h-walker-co-to-buy-laird-assets.html G. H. WALKER & CO. TO BUY LAIRD ASSETS].  New York Times, July 18, 1973</ref>  The company, later known as G.H. Walker, Laird & Co., was sold to [[White Weld & Co.]] in October 1974.<ref>[http://global.factiva.com/aa/?ref=NYTF000020050429dj2m00tj1 Weld & Co announces plans to take over G H Walker, Laird & Co.]  New York Times, October 1, 1974</ref><ref>[https://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=FB0F17F63F5F137B93C3A9178BD95F408785F9 MERGER PLANNED BY WHITE, WELD].  New York Times, October 1, 1974</ref>  White Weld, in turn, was sold to [[Merrill Lynch]] in 1978.

Other notable former employees include [[Bill Donaldson]], later founder of [[Donaldson, Lufkin & Jenrette]] and chairman of the [[Securities and Exchange Commission]].<ref>[http://articles.sfgate.com/2002-12-11/news/17573803_1_wall-street-william-donaldson-securities-industry Wall Street figure tapped to head SEC ].  San Francisco Chronicle, December 11, 2002</ref> [[George Herbert Walker III|Bert Walker]], later served as chairman and CEO of [[Stifel Financial]] in the late 1970s and 1980s.<ref>[http://www2.stifel.com/docs/pdf/AboutUs/StifelHistory.pdf History of Stifel Nicolaus]. (Stifel Financial website)</ref>

