{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}
{{Infobox person | honorific_prefix = ''[[Thai royal and noble titles#Ladies|Than Phu Ying]]'' | name = Lursakdi Sampatisiri | image = Thanpuying Lursakdi.jpg | caption = Thanpuying Lursakdi Sampatisiri in 1995 | spouse = Binich Sampatisiri | children = Bilhaiban Sampatisiri and Sanhapit Bodiratnangkura | birth_name = Lursakdi Sreshthaputa | birth_date = {{Birth date|1919|2|20}} | birth_place =[[Bangkok]], Thailand | death_date = {{Death date and age|2010|11|9|1919|2|20}} | death_place = [[Bangkok]], Thailand | occupation = Hotel owner, head of Nad Lert Group }}
[[Thai royal and noble titles#Ladies|Thanpuying]] '''Lursakdi Sampatisiri''' (20 February 1919{{spaced ndash}}9 November 2010; {{lang-th|เลอศักดิ์ สมบัติศิริ}}; {{RTGS|Loesak Sombatsiri}}; {{IPA-th|lɤːsàk sǒmbàtsìrì}}) was the daughter of [[Nai Lert|Nai Lert Sreshthaputa]] and the only heir of the business and real estate empire, founded in 1894, known as Nai Lert Group.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Legacy Lives On|url=http://www.nailertpark.com/the-legacy-lives-on.html|website=www.nailertpark.com|accessdate=11 June 2017}}</ref><ref>[http://www.nailertgroup.com/ Nai Lert Group website] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110210221650/http://nailertgroup.com/ |date=10 February 2011 }}</ref> As one of [[Thailand|Thailand’s]] most prominent businesswomen,<ref>{{cite book|title=Wives, Mistresses and Matriarchs: Asian Women Today |author=Louise Williams|url=http://search.barnesandnoble.com/Wives-Mistresses-and-Matriarchs/Louise-Williams/e/9780847691395/?itm=1|year=1999|publisher=[[Rowman & Littlefield Publishers, Inc.]]|isbn=978-0-8476-9139-5|page=115}}</ref> Sampatisiri created one of the first international hotels in Bangkok, The [[Hilton International|Hilton International Bangkok]] at Nai Lert Park. Today the hotel is known as [[Swissôtel Nai Lert Park Hotel]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Luxury Hotels & Resorts – Swissotel|url=http://www.swissotel.com|website=www.swissotel.com|accessdate=11 June 2017|language=en}}</ref> Bangkok, and remains the flagship of the real estate portfolio of the group.
==Early years== When Sampatisiri was a young woman (1930s), her father sent her to Japan, because he predicted that economic power would be centered there in her generation. She could only attend a college as Japanese universities did not accept women at that time. When she returned to Thailand, her father send her to work for the Office of [[Civil Servants]] Commission to find out how the Government worked. After three years of Government service, she returned to the family business, living, as she describes herself, a "life of privilege, rather than family duty, within Thailand's small economic elite" even though she had many responsibilities as sole heir.
Sampatisiri's father died suddenly, when she was 27 years old, and she found herself at the helm of his business empire which included the White Bus Company which dominated the Bangkok's transport routes (including its canals) and the ice factories which supplied the majority of the city's population. When Sampatisiri took over she became the first and only female in the company, but she convinced the managers to stay and keep the company going.
In 1930, she married Khun Binich Sampatisiri, who himself came from a prestigious background of public service. His father, Srisena Sampatisiri, served as ambassador to Japan and other countries in the 1930s and 1940s and was [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Thailand)|Thailand's Foreign Minister]] from 1944 to 1945, after which he served as [[Ministry of Interior (Thailand)|Minister of Interior]] in the 14th Thai Cabinet.<ref>{{cite web|title=The secretariat of the Cabinet|url=http://www.cabinet.thaigov.go.th/eng/cab_11.htm|website=www.cabinet.thaigov.go.th |accessdate=11 June 2017 |archivedate=14 January 2003 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030114191457/http://www.cabinet.thaigov.go.th/eng/cab_11.htm |date=14 January 2003}}</ref><ref>[http://www.cabinet.thaigov.go.th/eng/cab_11.htm Thai Government 11th Cabinet] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605013006/http://www.cabinet.thaigov.go.th/eng/cab_11.htm |date=5 June 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The secretariat of the Cabinet|url=http://www.cabinet.thaigov.go.th/eng/cab_14.htm|website=www.cabinet.thaigov.go.th|accessdate=11 June 2017 |archivedate=14 January 2003 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030114192540/http://www.cabinet.thaigov.go.th/eng/cab_14.htm |date=14 January 2003}}</ref> Khun Binich, himself, served as the Chief of the Traditional Arts Division of the [[Department of Fine Arts (Thailand)|Department of Fine Arts]] at the [[Ministry of Education (Thailand)|Ministry of Education]] for The [[Royal Thai Government]] and was a frequent host to overseas visitors and celebrities, being known for his sense of hospitality and entertainment (US comic [[Joey Adams]] mentions his encounter with Khun Binich in his book ''On The Road for Uncle Sam'').<ref>{{cite book|last=Adams|first=Joey|title=On the road for Uncle Sam|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BkBKAAAAMAAJ|year=1963|publisher=B. Geis Associates}}</ref>
== First woman in government == Seeing the coming of refrigeration, Lursakdi shifted her focus to transport. Unfortunately and suddenly, in 1975, the carefully-planned expansion of the transport business was swept away overnight by the chaos of Thai politics. After the government nationalized the Bangkok bus companies, which included the family run White Bus Company, Lursakdi, then [[Khunying]] Lursakdi, was invited by [[Thanin Kraivichien]], appointed Prime Minister by Royal Decree of [[King Rama IX]] on 8 October 1976, to join his cabinet as Minister of Transport thus making her the first female Minister in a Thai Government.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Cabinet |url=http://www.cabinet.thaigov.go.th/eng/cab_39.htm |website=www.cabinet.thaigov.go.th |accessdate=11 June 2017 |archivedate=14 January 2003 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030114193032/http://www.cabinet.thaigov.go.th/eng/cab_39.htm |date=14 January 2003}}</ref>
==Catering to the legacy== Lursakdi was, most recently, the chairperson of the business group that bears her father's name and also of the Lerd-Sinn Foundation which was created by her mother, Khunying Sinn, after the death of her father. The Lerd-Sinn Foundation, among other charitable activities, donated the proceeds used to build the Lerdsin hospital.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lerdsin Hospital|url=http://www.lerdsin.go.th/en/1.html|website=www.lerdsin.go.th|accessdate=11 June 2017}}</ref><ref>[http://www.lerdsin.go.th/ Lerdsin Hospital website]</ref> She represented the first of three generations of women who shaped the Nai Lert Park hotel in Bangkok and provided the strategic direction of the Nai Lert Group.<ref>[http://www.nationmultimedia.com/option/print.php?newsid=30078449 The Nation, 19 July 2008, Catering to a Legacy]{{deadlink|date=June 2017}}</ref> Her daughters, Bilhaiban Sampatisiri and Sanhapit Bodiratnangkura, as well as her granddaughter, Naphaporn Bodiratnangkura, were also engaged in the family business.
